A measure of the risk of a certain event happening in one group compared to the risk of the same event happening in another group. In cancer research, risk ratios are used in prospective (forward looking) studies, such as cohort studies and clinical trials. A risk ratio of one means there is no difference between two groups in terms of their risk of cancer, based on whether or not they were exposed to a certain substance or factor, or how they responded to two treatments being compared. A risk ratio of greater than one or of less than one usually means that being exposed to a certain substance or factor either increases (risk ratio greater than one) or decreases (risk ratio less than one) the risk of cancer, or that the treatments being compared do not have the same effects.

attributes.Name: a392a00a-60dc-4f56-af2b-cb99f6e1a086
attributes.simplified_text: Lumbar disc herniation is one of the most common causes of low back pain. Most people with lumbar disc herniation get better with conservative treatment, but some do not get better, and eventually need surgery.

attributes.Name: 70d7c6af-31f3-4c59-b860-4c38e2dd174d
attributes.simplified_text: There are several main surgical options for treating a herniated disc in the lumbar area of your spine: open lumbar micro-discectomy (OLM), microendoscopic discectomy (MED), minimally invasive transforaminal lumbar interbody fusion (MIS-TLIF), and percutaneous endoscopic lumbar discectomy (PELD). OLM has been regarded as the most commonly recommended surgical option for recurrent LD

attributes.Name: d04c7211-d1f2-4604-9902-4ead164995b2
attributes.simplified_text: PELD is a more minimally invasive surgery because the back bones are kept. It has gained interest for its potential advantage in the reduced risk of back bones getting hurt, fewer postoperative complications, a shorter hospital stay and lower cost. Previous studies have reported that PELD is an effective and safe treatment for LDH.

attributes.Name: 90db8b82-5bb0-4feb-84e1-10027717d4c4
attributes.simplified_text: We looked at many studies that compared surgery for LDH to see which one was better.

attributes.Name: d30896d9-0ffe-4da7-a094-d9668dcafa16
attributes.simplified_text: We searched multiple databases and found all the studies that we could find.

attributes.Name: 4bb733d0-8c2c-4434-afe7-8c042d4dd267
attributes.simplified_text: Figure 1. How the authors decided which studies to include in their analysis.

attributes.Name: 5719dd28-44a9-4351-b5e4-22c983b4db9a
attributes.simplified_text: This study looked at 14 different studies that included 2,528 people. It found that PELD surgery was faster and easier than the regular surgery and that it also made people feel better. However, it also found that PELD surgery was more likely to cause the disc to herniate again.

attributes.Name: 39551f3d-e442-4904-bacc-abd9693f9ba5
attributes.simplified_text: There were some limitations in this study. First, for some of the outcomes, the data analysis was based on a small number of studies and a small number of patients. Second, most of the studies were done by looking at medical records after patients had surgery. These studies were called 'retrospective' studies. One problem with retrospective studies is that they can't be as good as studies that are done by looking at patients before they have surgery.

attributes.Name: 3b638cf1-5509-42f1-9091-679321e21a7e
attributes.simplified_text: The researchers found that patients in the trials had these characteristics:

attributes.Name: 51ce452e-5a9e-4364-90b7-a7b9bf7910f5
attributes.simplified_text: For example, old age, obesity, and changes in the spine have been identified as significant risk factors for the PELD recurrence. And the 5 patients who experienced recurrence in the PELD group were all relatively old (≥60 years old) and obese; thus, they were at high risk of recurrent herniation.

attributes.Name: b7a6e4e7-e768-4759-a0da-c60019007de0
attributes.simplified_text: In the study, they compared the success rates of PELD and other surgeries. The success rate of PELD was 7.2%, and the success rate of other surgeries was 4.1%. The difference between them was not significant.

attributes.Name: f928fffe-5f84-475f-a4c6-a3aae15f117e
attributes.simplified_text: The study showed that the PELD surgery took less time than the other surgeries. The PELD surgery took 18 minutes less than the other surgeries.

attributes.Name: 8f0eb7b9-7f79-4c72-9d44-e0212cfd8ea1
attributes.simplified_text: The results showed that patients who had PELD surgery had the same level of pain as patients who had other surgeries. This is similar to what Yao Y, et al found. They found that the patients who had PELD surgery had the same level of pain as patients who had other surgeries. The level of pain was measured by a scale called the Visual Analog Scale (VAS). At the end of the study, the level of pain was the same in both groups.

attributes.summary: Lumbar disc herniation is one of the most frequently diagnosed causes of low back pain. There are several main surgical options: open lumbar microdiscectomy, microendoscopic discectomy, minimally invasive transforaminal lumbar interbody fusion, and percutaneous endoscopic lumbar discectomy.
We did this review in a way that follows a set of rules that other people can follow.

The study looked at patients who had a herniated disc and were having back and leg pain. The researchers wanted to see if PELD was better than other treatments. They looked at the success, recurrence, complication, operation time, hospital stay, blood loss, and pain scores.
Two people read the papers and wrote down the information they found.
We looked at the way the studies were done, and we looked at the way they were written.
Two people used a computer program to do the math.
This is meta-analysis, so we don't have to get permission from an ethics committee.
We found 2,374 papers that might be about what we're looking for.

This table shows the main characteristics of all the studies that were eligible for this review. In one study, Yao Y, et al. [45] performed a retrospective cohort study, in which three minimally invasive spine surgery approaches (PELD, MIS-TLIF, and MED) were used to treat patients with PELD recurrence. The median Jada score of the cohort studies was 6 (range from 5 to 8), indicating that these studies were of high quality.
The researchers looked at how well the treatment worked in different groups of people.

The study found that patients who had PELD surgery had a lower rate of complications than those who had microsurgical discectomy, but a similar rate of complications as those who had OLM, MIS-TLIF, MED, and fenestration discectomy.

Eleven studies reported the data of how long it takes to do the operation. Subgroup analysis based on the comparison showed that PELD is associated with a shorter operation time than OLM, MIS-TLIF, microsurgical discectomy, and microdisectomy, but a similar operation time with MED, fenestration discectomy, and open discectomy.

Eight studies reported the data of postoperation pain scores for back pain. Subgroup analysis based on comparators showed that PELD had a significantly lower pain score for back pain than open discectomy (WMD =  2.61, 95%CI:  4.0, 1.22; P < .001) and microdiscectomy (WMD =  0.50, 95%CI:  0.87, 0.13; P

Seven studies reported the data about how much leg pain hurt after surgery. When all the studies are combined, patients who had PELD surgery had the same amount of leg pain after surgery as patients who had other surgeries. However, when the studies are divided into groups, patients who had PELD surgery did not have the same amount of leg pain after surgery as patients who had other surgeries.

Three studies reported the data of SF12-MCS score. Subgroup analysis based on comparators showed that the greater SF12-MCS score of PELD was only observed in the comparison with MIS-TLIF (WMD=2.88, 95%CI: 0.67, 5.10; P = 0.011), but not in MED (WMD = 1.15, 95%CI: -1.95, 4.25; P=0.

There were three studies that looked at the SF-12 PCS, which is a measurement of how good someone feels. The researchers did a subgroup analysis of the PELD surgery compared to the MIS-TLIF surgery, and found that the PELD patients did better in the SF-12 PCS at one month, three months, six months, nine months, and twelve months.

In nine studies, the post-operation ODI score was reported. The analysis based on the comparators showed that PELD was comparable to other surgeries in terms of ODI score. The result was consistent across all the subgroups except for open discectomy, which showed a lower ODI score than PELD.

The researchers looked at the results of other studies on this topic, and they found that there was no evidence that the results were biased by the researchers' decisions to publish only some of their results.

A study looked at 14 studies and found that patients who had PELD surgery had shorter operation times, less blood loss, and better quality of life than patients who had other surgeries. However, the PELD patients also had a higher rate of having their disc herniate again. In this study, 7 out of 100 PELD patients had their disc herniate again, compared to 4 out of 100 patients who had other surgeries.

Eight studies reported the data of recurrence rate. Subgroup analysis based on the comparators showed that PELD had a higher recurrence rate than MIS-TLIF (14.86 vs 1.99), but a similar recurrence rate with OLM (1.01), MED (3.27), and microsurgical discectomy (1.22).
Six studies reported the data of hospital stay. Subgroup analysis based on comparators showed that, PELD significantly reduced the length of hospital stay as compared with other surgeries

Three studies reported the amount of blood loss patients had after surgery. The results showed that patients who had percutaneous endoscopic lumbar discectomy (PELD) had less blood loss than people who had other types of surgery. This benefit was seen in all the groups, including people who had a discectomy with a fenestration, people who had an open discectomy, and people who had a microdiscectomy.

Three studies reported the data of JOA score. The subgroup analysis showed that PELD was associated with a similar postoperation JOA score with other surgeries, and this was observed across all the subgroup analysis
